      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm having a nightmare with an embedded project for a car ECU. it's C++ and we have this slow memory leak that only shows up after like 4 or 5 hours of steady state operation. i can't find where the allocation isn't being freed. \n\nhere is the main telemetry loop:\n\nvoid process_sensor_data(SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet->status == VALID) {\n        DataLog* log = new DataLog(packet->payload);\n        log_store->push_back(log);\n        \n        if (log_store->size() > MAX_LOG_SIZE) {\n            // we should be cleaning up here but i can't track it down\n            log_store->remove_oldest(); \n        }\n    }\n}\n\ncan you help me figure out a systematic way to track down exactly where this leak is happening? i can't use heavy tools like Valgrind because of the hardware constraints.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in a resource-constrained ECU without Valgrind is a nightmare, but you can track it down methodically. First, you need to change your approach from hoping to find the leak to *measuring* it. Before the loop starts, log the total memory usage, and then periodically log it within the loop, especially after a few hundred sensor readings.\n\nIf you are using a custom memory allocator, you might be able to wrap `new` and `delete` operators to add bookkeeping—incrementing a counter on allocation and decrementing on deallocation. This gives you a simple, lightweight counter that tells you the net change in allocated memory over time, which should reveal if your cleanup isn't matching your allocation.\n\nFurthermore, scrutinize `log_store->remove_oldest()`. This is the most likely culprit; the `DataLog*` pointer being removed from the vector must be explicitly deleted using `delete` before the vector forgets about it. If `remove_oldest()` only removes the pointer from the `std::vector` without calling `delete` on the pointed-to object, you have a leak.",
      "source": "target",
