    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i'll check if remove_oldest is actually calling delete. but even if it's doing that, it's still hard to see the actual pattern. it's like the memory just creeps up bit by bit and disappears into the void. \n\nare there any other ways to catch it when it's being this subtle? like if it's not a straightforward missing delete, but maybe some weird fragmentation or a pointer getting lost in a different subsystem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the leak is subtle, the memory is likely being held by a persistent reference or a resource that isn't being properly released. I highly recommend inspecting the `DataLog` object itself; perhaps it's allocating internal buffers that aren't being cleaned up when the main `DataLog` object is deleted.\n\nYou should also implement a simple object tracking mechanism, even without heavy tools. Instead of just tracking raw bytes, track the *number* of `DataLog` objects created versus the *number* of objects successfully removed and deleted. If the count of allocated objects consistently exceeds the count of deleted objects, you have confirmed a leak, even if the memory doesn't immediately seem massive.\n\nIf the leak is due to fragmentation or a lost pointer in another subsystem, you need to trace the lifecycle of *every* dynamically allocated object. Consider adding a debug mechanism that assigns a unique ID to every `DataLog` upon creation and stores that ID in a global tracking structure. When `remove_oldest` runs, check if that ID is still referenced anywhere else by other parts of the ECU.",
      "source": "target",
